# Terraform AWS Instance Deployment

This repository contains Terraform code to deploy a new AWS instance. By following the instructions below, you can quickly spin up a new instance in your desired region using your preferred AMI and instance type.

## Prerequisites

Before you begin, make sure you have the following:

- Terraform CLI installed on your machine ([Terraform Installation Guide](https://learn.hashicorp.com/tutorials/terraform/install-cli))
- AWS CLI configured with appropriate credentials ([AWS CLI Configuration Guide](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/cli-configure-quickstart.html))

## Deployment Steps

To deploy a new instance, follow these steps:

1. Clone this repository to your local machine or download the provided `example.tf` file.

2. Open the `example.tf` file in a text editor.

3. Modify the following parameters in the code according to your requirements:
   - `region`: Replace the value with your desired AWS region.
   - `ami`: Replace the value with the AMI ID of the image you want to use.
   - `instance_type`: Replace the value with your desired instance type.

4. Save the changes to the `example.tf` file.

5. Open a terminal or command prompt and navigate to the directory where you saved the `example.tf` file.

6. Initialize the Terraform configuration by running the following command:


7. Apply the Terraform configuration to deploy the instance:


8. Review the changes that Terraform plans to make. If everything looks correct, type `yes` to confirm and proceed with the deployment.

9. Wait for Terraform to complete the deployment. Once finished, it will display the details of the newly created instance.

## Clean Up

To clean up and destroy the resources created by Terraform, follow these steps:

1. Open a terminal or command prompt and navigate to the directory where you saved the `example.tf` file.

2. Run the following command to destroy the deployed instance:


3. Review the changes that Terraform plans to make. If everything looks correct, type `yes` to confirm and proceed with the destruction.

4. Wait for Terraform to destroy the instance and associated resources.

